SPI Database Data Dictionary

06/01/2023

Database Overview

Disclaimer

The Salmonid Population Indicators (SPI) database is a work in progress and is subject to change.

Salmonid Population Indicators (SPI) Database

Since its genesis as the Salmon and Steelhead Stock Inventory (SASSI) in 1992 and then the Salmonid Stock Inventory (SaSI) in 1998, the Salmonid Population Indicators (SPI) database has consisted of:

  1. A standardized, uniform approach to identifying and monitoring the status of Washingtons naturally spawning salmonid populations of hatchery and natural-origin fish.
  2. The official list of salmonid populations recognized by the Washington Department of Fish and Wildlife and its co-managers.
  3. A database containing population status monitoring information and various metadata relevant to the constituent populations.

SPI is a cooperative product of the Washington Department of Fish and Wildlife and tribal co-managers and was intended to serve as a tool for prioritizing recovery efforts and measuring the results of recovery actions statewide. The co-managers original intent was to regularly update and revise the SaSI documents and, with the 1999 creation of the Salmonid Stock Conservation Biology Unit in the Fish Program, a comprehensive updating and revision of the SaSI documents was completed in 2002. In 2022 major changes were made to SPIs database structure and a new web-based data entry application was created. Additional fields were added based on StreamNets Coordinated Assessments Natural Origin Spawner Abundance (CA\NOSA) data exchange format. This latest addition is to provide a salmonid abundance dataset that contains better metadata and more monitoring parameters for more in-depth analysis.

SPI Core Tables Schema

What are the core tables in the SPI database? SPI core data tables include stock, stocK_data_series, and annual_data_detail.

  1. Stock contains general descriptions and metadata about the salmonid populations within Washington. It is currently read-only and is populated by the SPI data manager.
  2. Stock data series describes the data in annual data detail. It is currently read-only and is populated by the SPI data manager.
  3. Annual data detail contains the indicator data and supporting metrics. When data providers enter data in the Annual Data Entry page of the SPI Web Funnel, this is where the data is stored.

Database statistics

How much data is being entered in SPI? Counts of records in specific tables are indicated in the corresponding sections later in this document. The following plot shows trends of monthly abundance data counts made since 2008.

Where are SPI Populations located? The following map shows where SPI Populations are located. This section is still under development!!!

SPI Front End Application

SPI data providers can be granted access to a front end web application at: https://apps.wdfw-fish.us. This application allows users to check, add, edit, and delete abundance data. Access to data is limited to populations to which users are assigned.

Public Data Portal

SPI data contained in this system is mirrored on the WDFW open data portal at https://www.data.wa.gov. These datasets can be accessed directly through the public web portal, or via API. Data is refreshed in this system nightly.

Contact Information

For more information, please contact the SPI data manager Gil Lensegrav at gilbert.lensegrav@dfw.wa.gov .

stock

This table contains data that is descriptive in nature to individual salmonid populations. It is the primary table and is used to link to other databases or tables and provides a master list of all active or inactive salmonid populations. Linked to stock_data_series, nosa_event, stock_par_assignment, stock_report, management_goal (stock_id).

Total Records: 750

FieldName Nullable? DataType Descr
sasi_stock_num no character 4 digit numeric designation for each individual stock. Typically used for sorting purposes.
stock_name yes character varying Name of stock or population. In most cases the NOAA recognized population name is used.
active_ind no boolean Indicates if record is active in the current dataset.
gsro_stock_name yes character varying Population name used for the Governors State of the Salmon Report.
stock_id no uuid PK
geographic_area_lut_id no uuid The information in this field represents the geographical areas where each individual salmonid stock resides and/or utilizes watersheds throughout Washington State. Link to geographic_area_lut. See geographic_area_lut for more info.
gdu_lut_id yes uuid Genetic Diversity Unit (GDU) to which the stock belongs. GDUs are groups of genetically similar stocks. Link to gdu_lut. See gdu_lut.
mal_lut_id yes uuid Major Ancestral Lineage (MAL) to which the stock belongs. MALs are groups of similar GDUs. Link to mal_lut. See mal_lut
esa_unit_lut_id yes uuid This field defines the units of organization that are used for listing and delisting species under the Endangered Species Act (ESA). Link to esa_unit_lut. See esa_unit_lut.
mpg_lut_id yes uuid Major Population Group (MPG) to which the stock belongs. National Marine Fisheries Service Technical Recovery Teams grouping unit of fish population based on genetic measures, major habitat patterns (e.g., eco-regions), and life history variations. Link to mpg_lut.
sasi_run_lut_id no uuid Return time to freshwater. Most commonly used are spring, summer, fall, late fall, winter, spring/summer, summer/fall. Link to run_time_lut. See run_time_lut.
origin_lut_id no uuid Description of the genetic history or heritage of the stock. Link to origin_lut. See origin_lut.
predominant_production_type_lut_id no uuid Link to production_type_lut. See production_type_lut. Predominant method of spawning and rearing that produces the fish for the stock.
distinct_genetics_lut_id yes uuid Holds information on the distinctiveness of the genetics of a stock. Link to distinct_genetics_lut. See distinct_genetics_lut.
harvest_mgmt_unit_lut_id yes uuid Harvest Management Units are geographic areas with common harvest management goals for a given species spawning in the region. Link to harvest_mgmt_unit_lut. See harvest_mgmt_unit_lut.
parent_stock_id yes uuid For linking sub-populations to the parent populations stock_id.
bt_core_area_lut_id no uuid Bull trout core area, as defined by USFWS. Specific for bull trout. Link to bt_core_area_lut_id. See related table.
species_lut_id no uuid This field defines individual salmonid species. Link to species_lut. See species_lut for values.
nosa_popid yes bigint NOSA population id for the population(s) of fish represented by this record. For CA/NOSA data exchange purposes.
nosa_common_pop_name yes character varying Population name used by local biologists.
nosa_esu_dps_name yes character varying NA
nosa_esa_pop_name yes character varying NA
nosa_escapement_timing_lut_id yes uuid NA

annual_data_detail

This table contains annual data that is collected to monitor individual salmonid populations. The data reflects the best estimate of the overall health of the population. Linked to stock_data_series (fk stock_data_series_id).

Total Records: 24891

FieldName Nullable? DataType Descr
annual_data_yr no integer Beginning year in which the data was collected, compiled, or reported. Example: stocks that runin 2005 or from 2005-2006 would have Annual_Data_Yr=2005. Format: YYYY.
stock_abundance_qty yes numeric Contains a value reported by regional biologists as being the most current data for the associated stock. This value is used to chart current abundance trends and rate stock status for individual salmonid stocks.
comment_txt yes character varying Comments related directly to the relevant annual_data_detail_d record. Example: observational data; i.e.high water, low visibility.
cv_num yes numeric Coefficient of variation for the associated stock_abundance_qty. Coefficient of variation is the ratio between the standard deviation and the mean.
ci_num yes numeric Confidence interval for the associated stock_abundance_qty. Express these values as alpha values. For example, for the 95% confidence limits enter 0.05 in this field, not 95.
ci_lower_bound_num yes numeric The lower limit of the confidence interval. Minimum value = 0. If the calculated lower limit of the confidence interval is less than zero you may report 0 in this field, but we suggest you consider statistical options that prevent values outside of possible limits (these include non-normal distributions, transformations, and/or bootstrapping approaches).
ci_upper_bound_num yes numeric The upper limit of the confidence interval. Minimum value = 0.
annual_data_detail_id no uuid PK
abundance_qty_status_lut_id no uuid Describes the quality or status of the stock_abundance_qty value.
no_abundance_qty_reason_lut_id no uuid Describes the reason why stock_abundance_qty is left blank or null.
stock_data_series_id no uuid FK
co_mngr_agreement_status_lut_id yes uuid Describes whether the stock_abundance_qty was agreed-to by co-managers who are involved in the calculation process.
nosa_id yes uuid Used for StreamNets external data submissions, specifically the NOSA table.
methodadjustments_txt yes character varying Minor adjustments to a method in a given year that are not described in the methodology fields in the stock_data_series table but are important.
otherdatasources_txt yes character varying Identifies additional organizations, not listed in the stock_data_series table, that provided data or expertise to calculate the indicator(s), metric(s), or age distribution for this record.
nosa_best_value_lut_id yes uuid A declaration of whether the stock_data_series ContactAgency considers this record to be their approved best estimate for this combination of PopID and SpawningYear.
point_estimate_type_lut_id yes uuid NA

point_estimate_type_lut

Describes the type of sample data used to calculate a single value abundance quantity point estimate.

point_estimate_type_short_desc point_estimate_type_desc
mean The sum of the values divided by the number of values.
median The middle value separating the higher half from the lower half of adata sample, apopulation, or aprobability distribution.
mode The value that appears most often in a set of data values.

This may be any of the following: the name of a fluvial water body; the name of an impounded fluvial water body (reservoir); the name of a lentic water body; a description of multiple water bodies if appropriate for the time series; the name of a water body plus a dam, weir, trap, etc., if appropriate.

For example, if WaterBody = Wind River at Shipherd Falls enter -121.8050. Required if EstimateType = Escapement. Must be null if EstimateType = NOSA.
escapement_lat_meas yes numeric Use two digits left of the decimal point and four digits to the right of the decimal point. For example, if WaterBody = Wind River at Shipherd Falls enter 45.7371. Required if EstimateType = Escapement. Must be null if EstimateType = NOSA.

nosa_submit_agency_id yes uuid Initials or acronym for the agency, tribe, or other entity, or name of person, that sends this record of data to the CA-NOSA exchange network node at StreamNet. Note that it is possible for one entity to share data with another, and that second entity sends the record to the exchange network node. For example, the Makah Tribe may send data to WDFW, who in turn sends those data to the exchange network. In such a case the Makah Tribe would be identified as the contact agency for the data, but the Submit Agency would be WDFW. Linked to agency (FK agency_id).

data_type_lut

The Data Type describes the nature of the data. Each active population that is being monitored has at least one type of data that is entered into the database on an annual basis.

data_type_short_desc data_type_desc
Escapement Fish Fish that successfully pass through a fishery to reach the spawning grounds. This amount reflects losses resulting from harvest and natural mortality prior to enumeration but does not reflect pre-spawning mortality. Thus, escaped fish do not necessarily spawn successfully. If jacks or juveniles are included this needs to be noted in the comments.
HOSAEJ The point estimate for hatchery origin spawner abundance, excluding jacks. Includes only adults of hatchery origin, excluding jacks. Hatchery origin means the fishs parents spawned in a hatchery or artificially enhanced environment. Provide whole numbers only, not decimal values.
HOSAIJ The point estimate for hatchery origin spawner abundance, including jacks. Includes adults and jacks, all of hatchery origin. Hatchery origin means the fishs parents spawned in a hatchery or artificially enhanced environment. Provide whole numbers only, not decimal values.
HOSJF Hatchery origin spawner jack fraction. Express these values as numbers from zero to one, with three digits to the right of the decimal point.
NA Not applicable
NOBroodStockRemoved Natural origin broodstock removed. Provide whole numbers only, not decimal values. This value reflects fish taken for hatchery use. If it is known that no broodstock were taken it is preferable to enter 0 in this field rather than leaving it null.
NOSAEJ The point estimate for natural origin spawner abundance, excluding jacks. Includes only adults of natural origin, excluding jacks. Natural origin means the fishs parents spawned in the wild. Provide whole numbers only, not decimal values.
NOSAIJ The point estimate for natural origin spawner abundance, including jacks. Includes adults and jacks, all of natural origin. Natural origin means the fishs parents spawned in the wild. Provide whole numbers only, not decimal values.
NOSJF Natural origin spawner jack fraction. Express these values as numbers from zero to one, with three digits to the right of the decimal point.
PHOSEJ Point estimate for the proportion of fish spawning naturally, excluding jacks, that are hatchery origin fish. Express these values as numbers from zero to one, with up to three digits to the right of the decimal point.
PHOSIJ Point estimate for the proportion of fish spawning naturally, including jacks, that are hatchery origin fish. Express these values as numbers from zero to one, with up to three digits to the right of the decimal point.
Spawner Fish Live anddead fish on the spawning grounds.
Spawner Redds Redds on the spawning grounds.
TSAEJ The point estimate for total spawner abundance, excluding jacks. Provide whole numbers only, not decimal values.
TSAIJ The point estimate for total spawner abundance, including jacks. Provide whole numbers only, not decimal values.
Unknown Unknown data type.

stock_abundance_qty_type_lut

Describes the quantitative and qualitative indicator type represented by the abundance estimate.

stock_abundance_qty_type_short_desc stock_abundance_qty_type_desc
Index Final reported abundance quantity used to measure relative stock abundance. Only accounts for a portion of a stocks total abundance. The portion could be (but not limited to) geographic or temporal in nature. Example: raw redd counts from rm .5 to 1 plus rb trib rm 1 to 2, or fish counts at a dam for just the first 2 weeks of a spawning season
NA Not applicable
Total Final reported abundance quantity used to measure absolute stock abundance. Applies to the entire geographic area occupied by the stock and represents the stock as a whole. Example: total escapement for QuilceneBays Coho.
Unknown Unknown abundance area type.

stock_abundance_calcn_type_lut

Describes if the abundance estimate is expanded or modeled from a known quantity.

stock_abundance_calcn_type_short_desc stock_abundance_calcn_type_desc
Expanded Expanded, modeled, or multiplied from a raw number or quantity that was collected in the field. Example: total escapement modeled using AUC or expanded from raw redd counts using a model or calculation.
NA Not applicable
Unexpanded The quantity is a raw number or quantity that was collected in the field and is not modeled, expanded, or multiplied in any way. Example: total escapement represented by a raw adult trap fish count.
Unknown Unknown abundance calculation type.

nosa_age

Ages in this table are based on the year spawning occurred, not necessarily the year eggs hatched, so care must be taken in reporting ages. Assigning age can be complicated based on the life history (generally, salmon return and spawn in one year but hatch in the next, steelhead spawn and hatch in the same year). Make sure these details are accounted for in assigning ages. Linked to nosa_event (fk nosa_event_id).

Total Records: 1386

FieldName Nullable? DataType Descr
nosa_age_id no uuid PK
age2prop_qty yes numeric Values must be between 0 and 1. Express with 3 digits to the right of the decimal point. The age distribution numbers reported here must meet three criteria. If these criteria are not met then do not report ages: 1. These age fields contain proportions by age for the natural origin fish. They are not the numbers of fish actually aged, nor are they the expanded numbers for a population. Consider this scenario: 10,000 fish spawn (as reported in the NOSAIJ field); 500 fish were aged; after age analysis is completed it is determined that 1% of the fish (meaning 100 of the 10,000) were age 2. In this case the value in this field should be 0.01 (100/10,000) not 100, 500, or 10,000. Nor is it 0.2 (100/500). 2. The values of the Age2Prop through Age11PlusProp fields must sum to 1.00 0.01. 3. The age distribution must be derived only from the natural origin fish of the specific population this record represents. Therefore, do not include age data that are derived in part or in whole from any other group of fish. The age information may represent the exact group of spawning fish indicated in the NOSAIJ field, or a somewhat different group of fish. For example, the ages may represent the population as the fish passed a dam on their way to the spawning areas. Whatever may be the case, ensure this information is included in the protocol and method documentation.
age2proplowerlimit_qty yes numeric The associated alpha value is in the AgePropAlpha field, which is found below after the fields for age 11+. Minimum value = 0 and maximum = 1. If the calculated lower limit of the confidence interval is less than zero you may report 0 in this field, but we suggest you consider statistical options that prevent values outside of possible limits (these include non-normal distributions, transformations, and/or bootstrapping approaches).

If the calculated lower limit of the confidence interval is more than 1.0 you may report 1.0 in this field, but we suggest you consider statistical options that prevent values outside of possible limits.

management_goal_type_lut

Holds information on the type of management goal being tracked.

management_goal_type_name management_goal_type_desc
Broodstock The desired number of adult fish taken from broodstock during a spawning season. Report males and females together.
Critical Exploitation Rate Ceiling A fishery catch limitation calculated as the total fisheries mortality divided by the sum of total mortality plus escapement. Once escapement falls near or below a critical escapement level (low abundance threshold) Southern U.S. fisheries on the stock are managed to not exceed this ceiling.
Escapement Annual number of spawners thought to be needed for healthy production. May be based on historical escapement or an estimate of spawner carrying capacity. These are different from basin-wide escapement goals.
Exploitation Rate The number harvested divided by the total number in the runsize.
Low Abundance Threshold A spawning escapement level, set intentionally above the point of biological instability, which triggers extraordinary fisheries conservation measures to minimize fishery related impacts and increase spawning escapement.
Recovery Recovery goals defined and developed in one of the following ways: 1) minimum abundance thresholds based on intrinsic potential of historic habitat, locations and classifications of spawning areas, and abundance and productivity relationships that would result in a low (=5%) extinction risk within 100 years, and are associated with minimum productivity thresholds; 2) abundance goals developed to meet specific viability conditions as described in ESU, DPS, or regional recovery plans.
Recovery Exploitation Rate The maximum exploitation rate that will still permit recovery (growth) of a stock.
Recovery - GSRO Governors Salmon Recovery Office recovery goal of either minimum viability or low productivity.
Recovery - GSRO 2020 Governors Salmon Recovery Office recovery goal of either minimum viability or low productivity.
Recovery - High Productivity Target High productivity target number may represent: 1) the number of spawners at the point where the population provides the highest sustainable yield for every spawner, and productivity, number of adults returning per spawner, is expected to be greater then 1:1 and may be in the range of 3:1 to 4:1 (Puget Sound Salmon Recovery Plan; Shared Strategy & NOAA, 2007); or 2) viability goal to achieve <5% risk of extinction over 100 years when population productivity is high (Sands et al, 2009, Determination of independent populations and viability criteria for the Hood Canal summer chum salmon evolutionarily significant unit, NOAA Tech. Memo. NMFS-NWFSC-101).
Recovery - Low Productivity Target Low productivity target number may represent: 1) one adult fish returning from the sea for each spawner, also called the equilibrium point (1:1; Puget Sound Salmon Recovery Plan; Shared Strategy & NOAA, 2007); or 2) viability goal to achieve <5% risk of extinction over 100 years when population productivity is low (Sands et al, 2009, Determination of independent populations and viability criteria for the Hood Canal summer chum salmon evolutionarily significant unit, NOAA Tech. Memo. NMFS-NWFSC-101).
Recovery - Maximum Viable Target Viable population size guidelines developed by NOAA Fisheries defined in the following way: Population abundance that is the smaller of a habitat-based capacity estimate and estimate from population viability analysis (PVA) using particular conditions for growth rate and growth rate variance that resulted in an extinction probability equal to or less than 0.01, and represents the high end of recovery goal range (e.g., Rawson et al.2009. Viability Criteria for the Lake Ozette sockeye salmon ESU. NOAA Tech. Memo. NMFS-NWFSC-99);
Recovery - Minimum Viable Target Viable population size guidelines developed by NOAA Fisheries defined in one of following ways: 1) population abundance large enough to a) survive normal environmental variation, b) allow compensatory processes to provide resilience to perturbation, c) maintain genetic diversity, d) provide important ecological functions, and e) not risk effects of uncertainty in status evaluations; or 2) population abundance based on population viability analysis (PVA) using particular conditions for growth rate and growth rate variance that resulted in an extinction probability equal to or less than 0.05, and represents the low end of recovery goal range (e.g., Rawson et al.2009. Viability Criteria for the Lake Ozette sockeye salmon ESU. NOAA Tech. Memo. NMFS-NWFSC-99); or 3) population abundance that meets a minimum delisting threshold in the context of entire DPS/ESU viability criteria (e.g., Mid-Columbia steelhead & Yakima steelhead recovery plans)
Restoration WDFWs desired annual run size, above and beyond ESA recovery.
Upper Management Threshold An upper escapement level that serves as the threshold for determining whether a management unit has a harvestable surplus of fish (i.e., above this level there is a surplus). This is the escapement level associated with optimum productivity unless otherwise agreed to.
